problem_text: In the figure, m \angle 1 = 123. Find the measure of \angle 14.
proof:
Step 1:
Theorem: Known facts
Premises : start
Conclusions: ∠IHL, ∠LFA, ∠JHL, ∠GHF, ∠LHG, 3.14 = pi, H on GI, H on FL, I on HJ, ∠FHI, ∠BHI, I on GJ, ∠KIG, ∠BHJ, F on BH, ∠KEA, I on EK, ∠BFD, F on AE, BL || CK, AD || GJ, E on DF, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠LHG

Step 2:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : ∠LFA, H on FL
Conclusions: ∠HFA = ∠LFA

Step 3:
Theorem: Vertical Angle Theorem
Premises : H on GI, H on FL
Conclusions: ∠GHF = ∠IHL

Step 4:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : I on HJ, ∠JHL
Conclusions: ∠IHL = ∠JHL

Step 5:
Theorem: Circumference Split
Premises : ∠GHF, ∠FHI, ∠IHL, ∠LHG
Conclusions: 2 * pi = ∠FHI + ∠GHF + ∠IHL + ∠LHG

Step 6:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : H on GI, ∠KIG
Conclusions: ∠KIG = ∠KIH

Step 7:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : ∠BHJ, F on BH
Conclusions: ∠BHJ = ∠FHJ

Step 8:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : ∠BHI, F on BH
Conclusions: ∠BHI = ∠FHI

Step 9:
Theorem: Vertical Angle Theorem
Premises : I on EK, I on GJ
Conclusions: ∠GIE = ∠JIK

Step 10:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : ∠KEA, F on AE
Conclusions: ∠KEA = ∠KEF

Step 11:
Theorem: Corresponding Angle Theorem
Premises : BL || CK
Conclusions: ∠JHL = ∠JIK

Step 12:
Theorem: Alternate Interior Angle Theorem
Premises : BL || CK
Conclusions: ∠BHI = ∠KIH, ∠BFE = ∠KEF

Step 13:
Theorem: Alternate Interior Angle Theorem
Premises : AD || GJ
Conclusions: ∠DEI = ∠GIE, ∠FHJ = ∠HFA

Step 14:
Theorem: Corresponding Angle Theorem
Premises : AD || GJ
Conclusions: ∠KEA = ∠KIG, ∠BFD = ∠BHJ, ∠LFA = ∠LHG

Step 15:
Theorem: Same Angle
Premises : E on DF, ∠BFD
Conclusions: ∠BFD = ∠BFE

Step 16:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠IHL = ∠JHL, ∠JHL = ∠JIK
Conclusions: ∠IHL = ∠JIK

Step 17:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠DEI = ∠GIE, ∠GIE = ∠JIK
Conclusions: ∠DEI = ∠JIK

Step 18:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠KEA = ∠KIG, ∠KEA = ∠KEF
Conclusions: ∠KEF = ∠KIG

Step 19:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠LFA = ∠LHG, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠LHG
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠LFA

Step 20:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠IHL = ∠JIK, ∠GHF = ∠IHL
Conclusions: ∠GHF = ∠JIK

Step 21:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠KEF = ∠KIG, ∠BFE = ∠KEF
Conclusions: ∠BFE = ∠KIG

Step 22:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : pi * (123 / 180) = ∠LFA, ∠HFA = ∠LFA
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠HFA

Step 23:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠BFD = ∠BHJ, ∠BFE = ∠KIG, ∠BFD = ∠BFE
Conclusions: ∠BHJ = ∠KIG

Step 24:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠FHJ = ∠HFA, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠HFA
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠FHJ

Step 25:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠BHJ = ∠KIG, ∠KIG = ∠KIH
Conclusions: ∠BHJ = ∠KIH

Step 26:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : pi * (123 / 180) = ∠FHJ, ∠BHJ = ∠FHJ
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠BHJ

Step 27:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠BHJ = ∠KIH, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠BHJ
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠KIH

Step 28:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠BHI = ∠KIH, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠KIH
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠BHI

Step 29:
Theorem: Transtivity of Equivalence
Premises : ∠BHI = ∠FHI, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠BHI
Conclusions: pi * (123 / 180) = ∠FHI

Step 30:
Theorem: Substitution
Premises : 3.14 = pi, ∠GHF = ∠JIK, ∠IHL = ∠JIK, 2 * pi = ∠FHI + ∠GHF + ∠IHL + ∠LHG, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠LHG, pi * (123 / 180) = ∠FHI
Conclusions: 2 * 3.14 = 3.14 * (123 / 180) + 3.14 * (123 / 180) + ∠JIK + ∠JIK

Step 31:
Theorem: Solve Linear Equation System
Premises : ∠DEI = ∠JIK, 2 * 3.14 = 3.14 * (123 / 180) + 3.14 * (123 / 180) + ∠JIK + ∠JIK
Conclusions: 0.99 = ∠DEI
